  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a property you have inherited is different from selling your own home in almost every practical way. Before a sale can proceed, someone needs to have the legal authority to act on behalf of the estate. That authority does not arise automatically when a person passes away. It needs to be established through the Queensland court system, and the process can take several months depending on the complexity of the estate and whether the deceased left a valid will.</p>

      <p>The emotional dimension adds another layer of difficulty. Selling a family home, even one that is no longer practical to keep, often involves navigating grief and competing family expectations while simultaneously managing a legal and financial process. Understanding what is required before you are ready to sell, and what the common delays are, makes the whole process easier to manage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Establishing the authority to sell</h2>
      <p>Before a property can be sold, the person managing the sale needs to have established legal authority over the estate. If the deceased left a valid will that names an executor, that executor needs to apply for a Grant of Probate from the Supreme Court of Queensland. Probate is the court's formal recognition that the will is valid and that the executor has authority to administer the estate, including selling real property.</p>

      <p>If the deceased did not leave a will, there is no named executor. In that case, a family member or other interested party must apply for Letters of Administration, which serve a similar purpose. This process takes longer and requires a different set of documents. The person appointed as administrator has the same authority as an executor once the letters are granted.</p>

      <p>Without one of these documents in place, a real estate agent cannot list the property and a conveyancer cannot complete a sale. Getting the application lodged early, ideally within a few weeks of the death, shortens the overall timeline considerably. Queensland probate applications typically take four to eight weeks to process once all supporting documents are in order, though more complex estates can take longer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When multiple beneficiaries inherit jointly</h2>
      <p>One of the most common complications in deceased estate sales arises when the property passes to multiple beneficiaries under the will, or to multiple family members under intestacy rules. In Queensland, all beneficiaries who have an interest in the property generally need to agree on the key decisions: whether to sell, when to sell, how to price the property, and which agent to appoint.</p>

      <p>This is straightforward when everyone is in agreement and communication is open. It becomes difficult when beneficiaries have different financial situations, different emotional attachments to the property, or different views on timing. Some family members may want to sell quickly to access their inheritance; others may want to hold the property, renovate it first, or wait for what they believe will be better market conditions.</p>

      <p>If beneficiaries cannot reach agreement, the options narrow significantly. In some cases a beneficiary can apply to the court for an order to sell the property, but this is a costly and slow process that tends to benefit nobody. Far better outcomes come from early, structured conversations among all parties about what each person actually needs from the sale. An experienced solicitor can help facilitate this, and is well worth engaging at the outset.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">CGT on inherited property in Queensland</h2>
      <p>The Capital Gains Tax treatment of an inherited property depends on when the deceased acquired the property and what they used it for. The rules are set at the federal level and apply across Australia, but the practical effect varies considerably depending on the circumstances.</p>

      <p>As a general principle, if the deceased acquired the property before 20 September 1985 (the pre-CGT era), the estate will generally not have a CGT liability on the property itself. Beneficiaries who then sell the property may have a liability depending on how long they hold it after receiving it and what happens to its value during that time.</p>

      <p>If the property was the deceased's main residence and passes to a beneficiary who then sells it within two years, the sale may be fully or partially exempt from CGT. Holding the property for longer than two years before selling generally reduces or eliminates that exemption. The two-year window is important and worth tracking from the date of death.</p>

      <p>If the property was an investment property rather than the deceased's main residence, CGT will typically apply to the gain from the date the deceased acquired it to the date of sale. The estate (and ultimately the beneficiaries) will be liable for this. Getting advice from a tax accountant or solicitor early in the process helps avoid surprises at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to handle an inherited property that still has a tenant</h2>
      <p>If the deceased was a landlord and the property has a current tenant, the lease continues in full force after the death. The estate steps into the role of landlord. Existing lease terms, rent payment arrangements, and the tenant's rights under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (Qld) all continue unchanged.</p>

      <p>The executor or administrator needs to notify the tenant of the change of management in writing, provide updated contact details, and ensure the bond lodgement is accounted for correctly. The property can be listed for sale while tenanted, but the agent and executor need to comply with the Queensland rules around entry notices for open homes and inspections, which require at least 24 hours notice and must be conducted at reasonable times.</p>

      <p>A good tenant can actually be an advantage in some sales, particularly for investors looking to acquire a property with immediate rental income. The marketing should reflect the current tenancy status clearly and honestly. Buyers who intend to occupy the property themselves will need to understand when vacant possession can be provided, which depends on the type of tenancy (fixed term or periodic) and the relevant notice requirements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common delays and how to avoid them</h2>
      <p>The most frequent cause of delay in deceased estate sales is the probate or letters of administration process taking longer than expected because documents are incomplete when lodged. Gathering and verifying the necessary supporting documents, including the original will, death certificate, and information about the estate's assets, takes time. Starting the process early and engaging an experienced estate solicitor significantly reduces this risk.</p>

      <p>The second most common delay is disagreement among beneficiaries. As noted above, early structured conversations about expectations and needs prevent the kind of entrenched positions that lead to months of delay or, in the worst cases, litigation. A family mediator or solicitor with estate administration experience can help facilitate these conversations.</p>

      <p>Property maintenance is another practical issue. An unoccupied inherited property still needs to be insured, secured, and maintained. Insurers typically require notification within a short period of the property becoming unoccupied, and some policies exclude claims on properties that have been vacant for more than a specified time. Checking the policy and notifying the insurer early avoids complications later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Choosing an agent who understands deceased estate sales</h2>
      <p>Not every real estate agent has experience managing deceased estate sales, and the differences in process and sensitivity required are significant. An agent handling a deceased estate sale needs to understand the additional legal steps involved, be comfortable working with solicitors and accountants as part of a team, and be capable of managing communications with multiple beneficiaries who may have different priorities and levels of engagement.</p>

      <p>The marketing approach also needs to be considered carefully. Some executors prefer not to advertise the deceased estate nature of the sale, to avoid the perception that it is a distressed or below-market sale. Others are comfortable with it, recognising that some buyers are specifically looking for deceased estate properties because they expect a fair price without the complications of a motivated seller's expectations. The right approach depends on the property, the location, and the target buyer profile.</p>

      <p>Daniel has handled a number of deceased estate sales in Brisbane's inner east and understands both the process and the emotional weight that comes with it. If you are managing an inherited property and want an honest conversation about your options and the likely timeline, get in touch.</p>

